    <!-- H2: What Is an Xbox Gamertag? -->
    <div class="mb-5 md:mb-7">
      <h2 class="text-brand text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight leading-tight mb-1">
        What Is an Xbox Gamertag?
      </h2>
      <p class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed mb-4">
        A gamertag is your public name on Xbox — your online alias, your virtual identity. It is the name other players see when you join a lobby, drop into a match, or top the leaderboard. It shows up on your profile, on friend lists, and across Xbox Live, Game Pass, and cloud gaming.
      </p>
      <p class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed mb-5">
        Microsoft introduced gamertags when Xbox Live launched in 2002 as a way to give every player a unique online presence. It is your gamer username — but with more personality. This is what people remember you by.
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-dark-heading text-base md:text-lg font-bold leading-snug mb-1">
        Classic vs. Modern Gamertags
      </h3>
      <p class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Not all Xbox names are created equal. There are two main types:
      </p>
      <ul class="space-y-3 pl-5 list-disc mb-5">
        <li class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed">
          <strong class="text-dark-heading font-semibold">Classic Gamertags</strong> — the originals. Short, clean names with no numbers and no suffixes. Think SniperWolf or TacticalToast. Pure and iconic. The catch is most of these are long gone.
        </li>
        <li class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed">
          <strong class="text-dark-heading font-semibold">Modern Gamertags</strong> — introduced with the newer Xbox system. You can now pick almost any name even if someone else already has it. Xbox adds a number suffix behind the scenes to keep each account unique. So you can still get ShadowBlade — it will just come with a tag like #1278 attached.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3 class="text-dark-heading text-base md:text-lg font-bold leading-snug mb-1">
        A Brief History of the Gamertag
      </h3>
      <p class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed mb-5">
        When Xbox Live launched in 2002, having a unified online name was a new idea. No more Player1 or Guest123 — you had a gamertag and it was yours. As the player base grew, so did the demand for unique names. Microsoft eventually moved to the current suffix system so players could still use popular names without blocking others from having them.
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-dark-heading text-base md:text-lg font-bold leading-snug mb-1">
        What Your Gamertag Says About You
      </h3>
      <p class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Like it or not, people judge your tag. A good one says you are creative, memorable, or just downright funny. A bad one makes it hard to be taken seriously in any lobby. Your gamertag is your gamer brand — it should say something about your style without trying too hard.
      </p>
      <p class="text-[#374151] text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed">
        That is exactly what this generator is built for. Whether you are just starting out, rebranding your gaming identity, or looking for something that feels more like you — use the tool above to generate names that are not just available, but actually worth keeping.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- H2-1: How the Generator Works -->
